{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e9061b7b-f3e4-4873-9e11-9f079402dae8","content":"This is a TUnit project (MTP-native), so use `--treenode-filter` instead of VSTest's `--filter`:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test --treenode-filter \"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests/*\"\n```\n\nThe treenode filter path format is `/Assembly/Namespace/Class/Test`, so `/*/*/SmsNotificationTests/*` matches any assembly, any namespace, the `SmsNotificationTests` class, and all its test methods.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a5d6a14f-9266-440c-94f3-5b93b6430ce9","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"This is a TUnit project. TUnit uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP) natively. For MTP-based projects, the filter syntax is different from VSTest.\n\nFor TUnit with MTP, you use `--treenode-filter` to filter tests. To filter by class name, the syntax is:\n\n```\ndotnet test --treenode-filter \"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests\"\n```\n\nOr you can use the `--filter` option if VSTest compatibility is enabled, but since this project uses TUnit which is MTP-native, the correct approach is `--treenode-filter`.\n\nActually, let me think about this more carefully. \n\nThe treenode filter path format follows `/Assembly/Namespace/Class/Test`, so to match all tests in the SmsNotificationTests class, I'd use wildcards to capture the assembly and namespace parts, then specify the class name followed by another wildcard for individual tests. I'm reconsidering whether `dotnet test` with MTP also supports the standard `--filter` option, or if `--treenode-filter` is the only way to go with TUnit.","outputTokens":528,"requestId":"3401:2317F5:B641E9:D43733:69F40216"},"id":"2c729fdc-3cc3-40bb-bcc8-942860096c67","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:30:10.931Z","parentId":"55ed98d7-46ef-4a72-aa6a-b1179ce7676b"}
